<DOC><DOCNO> AP880823-0199 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0014EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2takes   08-23 0535</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0559</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Several big Wall Street firms still are heavilyengaged in program trading while small investors are avoiding thestock market, according to statistics released by the New YorkStock Exchange.   The NYSE's first monthly report on program trading provided someof the most detailed figures yet available on the short-term andhighly profitable trading technique, blamed by some studies forplaying a role in the stock market crash and subsequent volatilitythat has frightened away investors.   The report released Monday showed program trading in Julyaccounted for 10.1 percent of the exchange's average daily tradingvolume.</TEXT><DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A management group's offer to takeWickes Cos. Inc. private in a $598 million leveraged buyout hasbrought numerous inquiries from other potential buyers.   The $12-a-share tender offer, made late Sunday by a managementgroup led by Wickes Chairman Sanford Sigoloff, included a 60-daywait before the group would begin buying Wickes stock, to giveother bidders a chance to emerge.   Numerous potential buyers called Monday, according to BearStearns andamp; Co. Inc., which was retained to advise Wickes managementon the offer.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The management of Lear Siegler Seating Corp.says it has agreed to purchase the company from Forstmann Little andamp;Co. in a buyout valued at $500 million.   Management is being financed in part by the investment firmKidder, Peabody Group Inc., which will take an undisclosed equitystake in the company, according to Monday's announcement.   Forstmann, a leveraged buyout firm, acquired Lear Siegler in1986 for $2.1 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   If farmers boost plantings and the droughteases, this year's massive drain on the U.S. wheat stockpile couldbe brought under control in 1989, the Agriculture Department says.   Total wheat supplies in the 1988-89 marketing year that began onJune 1 are estimated at about 3.1 billion bushels, down more than20 percent from last season and the lowest in almost a decade, thedepartment's Economic Research Service said in an outlook reportMonday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Chubb Corp. wants to make sure thissummer's drought doesn't claim another victim along with parchedcrops: its good name.   Stung by criticism it backed away from drought insurance andleft thousands of farmers high and doubly dry, Chubb has set up acrisis center, mobilized phone-answering troops for toll-freenumbers and taken out newspaper ads.   Chubb has said applications for the insurance far exceeded theoriginal $30 million in coverage it had authorized. The companylater increased the authorized amount to $40 million.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Farmers hit hard by this year's drought shouldthink about enrolling highly erodible cropland in the long-termConservation Reserve Program, the Agriculture Department says.   The current signup period for the CRP will end on Aug. 31. Morethan 25.5 million acres have been enrolled in previous signups, andthe goal is to have 40 million to 45 million acres in the programby the end of 1990.   Under the program, farmers offer bids to take land from cropproduction and plant it to grass or trees for 10 years as a guardagainst erosion.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>